<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18511027-1974">
               <interp inst="t18511027-1974" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18511027"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18511027-1974" type="date" value="18511027"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18511027-1974-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1974-18511027 t18511027-1974-offence-1 t18511027-1974-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1974. <persName id="def1-1974-18511027" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1974-18511027" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1974-18511027" type="age" value="28"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1974-18511027" type="surname" value="ANSELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1974-18511027" type="given" value="SPENCER"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">SPENCER ANSELL</hi>
                  </persName>, was <hi rend="italic">again</hi> indicted<rs id="t18511027-1974-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18511027-1974-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18511027-1974-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="embezzlement"></interp> for embezzlement.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HUDDLESTON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-857" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-857" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-857" type="surname" value="FRANCIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-857" type="given" value="ALFRED"></interp>ALFRED FRANCIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in partnership with Charles Francis and another—we are cement-manufacturers at Nine Elms, and carry on business in Great Scotland-yard—the prisoner was employed to manage our business at Great Scotland-yard—we furnished him with cement for the purpose of sale at that place—he had permission to sell the articles on cash and on credit—I myself</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185110270173"></xptr>
               <p>called there to see how business was going on—when he sold goods he was to enter them in his day-book—he was in the habit of furnishing his stock-paper weekly to our counting-house—I have here his stock-paper of 11th Sept; it contains the account of goods, showing the stock on hand of the preceding week—in addition to that, the stock he had received since from us—he charged himself with them, and he discharged himself by cash credit and expenses—it was his duty to pay over the balance to our cashier, George Judd—this is the stock-paper of 11th Sept.—it is the prisoner's writing—I took it from him—it is not finished—his expenses are not added to it—it would appear in the day-book to whom he had sold goods.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARNELL</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you anything in the world to do with this man yourself, either by employing him, or receiving the accounts from him, or receiving money from him, or giving him direction? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I employed him, as one of the partners—he was in our employ some years as a labouring man—I did not pay him his wages—I took this stock-paper from him before it was completed—I was not in the habit of receiving his papers, or receiving money or accounts from him; that was all done through out cashier—the prisoner was employed at Great Scotland-yard, and he was employed at Nine Elms before we put him there—he was employed the last two or three years at Scotland-yard—he had to come to Nine Elms to give in his accounts—his wages were 20<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week—he had been with us probably six or seven years—we have filled up his place since he left, and we are giving higher wages.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HUDDLESTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> In what respect is this paper not complete? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I think he has not charged his expenses—he has mentioned here the amount of goods sold—he was transcribing it from the slate and the day-book when I entered the warehouse.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-858" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-858" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-858" type="surname" value="KEEF"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-858" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE KEEF</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a builder, and live in King-street, Soho. I deal with Messrs. Francis—I obtained goods from the prisoner at Scotland-yard—on 4th June I paid him 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; he gave me this receipt.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> This is, I see, a bill made out in the name of Ansell; did you know about Francis' being in the business? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I knew they were in the business—I got the things from the prisoner—I never saw anything of Francis in the matter—I had dealt with the prisoner for some time before this—this was a payment in part of the account—there was 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 5 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>. left to pay to make it all right—I have paid another account since—I suppose this was added to the other.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HUDDLESTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Is not the name "Francis" over the door, in Scotland-yard? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I dealt at the yard previous to the prisoner being there—I paid the money with the intention of paying it into the firm, on account of the goods I had had from the yard.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-859" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-859" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-859" type="surname" value="LAYCOCK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-859" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM LAYCOCK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a builder, and live in Hill-street, Berkley-Square; I have dealt with Messrs. Francis for cement On 23rd July I sent. Fitzgerald for some cement—I gave him 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; there were two empty casks to be returned—he brought back the goods—I sent him for 9<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. change, and a receipt for the money—this is it; the amount of the cement is 17<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; here is an allowance for the casks, and 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. paid in money—he brought me 9<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and this bill.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-860" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-860" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-860" type="surname" value="FITZGERALD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-860" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS FITZGERALD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in Mr. Laycock's service—in July I got 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. from him—I gave it to some one in the office, I really cannot tell who, as it is some time ago—I received from the person this receipt and the change—I cannot tell how much change I got—I saw the mail write this receipt—I had been to that place once before.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185110270174"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-861" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-861" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-861" type="surname" value="FRANCIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-861" type="given" value="ALFRED"></interp>ALFRED FRANCIS</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> This bill is the prisoners' writing—it is "Paid, S. Ansell."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-862" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-862" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-862" type="surname" value="BEACH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-862" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>ELIZABETH BEACH</persName>
                  </hi>. My husband is a builder. He deals with Messrs. Francis for cement—I know the prisoner as warehouseman at Scotland-yard. On 11th Sept. I paid him 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I got this receipt from him for 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 7 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-863" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-863" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-863" type="surname" value="JUDD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-863" type="given" value="GEORGE WILLIAM"></interp>GEORGE WILLIAM JUDD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am cashier to Messrs. Francis. I have been there twenty-six years—the prisoner was warehouseman in my masters' employ—it was his duty to sell the goods of Messrs. Francis in the yard—he had a check-book, and when he sold goods it was his duty to make out a check as a bill and receipt if the goods were sold for cash, and give that to the party who bought the goods; and if they were sold on credit, the goods were merely filled in—the counterfoil remained attached to the book—it was his duty to make out a weekly stock-paper—it consisted of the goods that had been sold during the week from the Friday to the Thursday night—he was to enter in the day-book the money and goods sold on credit—he brought the stock-paper and books to me every week—I used to look at the account and receive the money from him—the amount of cash in the stock-paper I compared with the amount in his day-book, and if they agreed I took the balance from him—he paid me at the time—the day-book was the voucher to me for the moneys that had been received by him—I considered that every. thing ought to be entered in the day-book—I looked at the day-book to see what had been received by him—I have the day-book here—I have com<lb></lb>pared it with the stock-papers from Jan. to Sept.—I have found that the stock-papers agree with the day-book—I do not find any entry in the day-book of 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. received from Mr. Keith, or 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. from Laycock, or 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 7 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>. from Beach.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How often was this book brought to you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Every Friday night, almost invariably—it has been on Saturday—I do not recollect that it ever went two weeks—the money received is, on both sides of this book, made up a total at the end of the week—it was by this book and the stock-paper he paid me the money—the book and the stock-papers agree as to the amount—he gave me the stock-paper and what appeared there—he occasion<lb></lb>ally left the book with me—from 23rd May till 11th June I was absent—Mr. Friend was there then—the prisoner has come sometimes on Friday evening and sometimes on Saturday—he has come when I was not there—in one or two instances I think he left the book with the wharf-clerk; but when I had the book the paper was in it, and I found the book and paper to agree—he might have left it with one of my fellow-clerks, but I do not recollect such an instance—this book is in his handwriting—there were no other clerks at Scotland-yard who might have made entries while he was there—there was no one but himself—if a large quantity of cement were delivered he would get assistance.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How often did you examine the counterfoils and the stock-paper with the day-book? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I examined the cash at the time—it was no part of my duty to examine the counterfoils with the book—that was done by a clerk at Nine Elms—he is not here; the book is.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HUDDLESTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When he gave these bills to the customers, was it his duty to enter this money in the day-book? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I was sometimes out when he came with money—I compared the day-book and stock-paper with the balance of money that had been left—I did that in all cases, and found it correct—I received from him, during the period I have mentioned, the sums that appeared to be entered in the book—the whole of the money entered in this book, and of course in the stock-papers, I received, and found it correct—I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185110270175"></xptr>
               <p>did not in these accounts receive this 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., or 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., or 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 7 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—if in the way of his duty he had entered them as he ought to have done, either I or Mr. Friend would have received them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-864" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-864" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-864" type="surname" value="FRIEND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-864" type="given" value="JOHN EWEN"></interp>JOHN EWEN FRIEND</persName>
                  </hi>. I have been in the prosecutors' employ fourteen or fifteen years. From 23rd May to 11th June it was my duty to receive the day-book, the stock-papers, and cash from the prisoner—I found the day-book and stock-papers were correct as far as was stated—here is no entry of a payment of 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. by Keef, on 4th June.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> You did not know of Mr. Keef's existence? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; all the sums are put down with a name—if a man went there and bought goods without a name, it would be the prisoner's duty to ask his name—it is the custom of our trade to have the name of everybody, because we want to follow up the trade if we can—I never recollect seeing an entry without a name.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HUDDLESTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you know the prisoner's writing? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; these receipts of Mr. Beach, Mr. Laycock, and Mr. Keef are his writing—I have no doubt.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-865" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-865" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-865" type="surname" value="CAPON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-865" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS CAPON</persName>
                  </hi>. I took stock at Scotland-yard on 11th Sept I found a deficiency in the stock of 989 bushels of Roman cement, 48 cwt. of plaster, 49 bushels of Parian cement, and 1,808 lbs. of mastic.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JUDD</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you the counterfoil-book here? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; this is the prisoner's handwriting—here are a number of leaves deficient—here is no counterfoil of Laycock's.</p>
               <p>(<hi rend="italic">The prisoner received a good character.</hi>)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18511027-1974-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-1974-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-1974-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>. Aged 28.—
